=> Before Java8, we were using :
    -> java.util.Date
    -> java.util.Calendar
    -> java.util.SimpleDateFormat

=> Problems with old Date and Calendar API:
    -> Not thread safe
    -> Mutable objects
    -> Poor API design

=> JSR(Java Specification Request) 310 introduced a new Date and Time API in the java.time package in Java 8, which is based on the ISO(International Organization for Standardization) calendar system and inspired by the Joda-Time library.

    -> Problems with old Date and Time API:
        -> java.util.Date was mutable and not thread-safe.
        -> Calendar API was complex and difficult to use.
        -> SimpleDateFormat was not thread-safe.
        -> Poor timezone handling.
        -> Confusing design and deprecated methods.

    -> Advantages of new Date and Time API:
        -> Immutable and thread-safe classes.
        -> Clear separation between date, time, and timezone.
        -> Better timezone support.
        -> Easy formatting and parsing.
        -> Fluent and readable API design.
        -> Supports multiple calendar systems.

    -> main packages of Date and Time API:

        -> java.time:
            -> Contains the core classes for date and time manipulation, such as LocalDate, LocalTime, LocalDateTime, ZonedDateTime, etc.

            -> Important class in java.time package:

                -> LocalDate:
                    -> Represents a date without time.
                    -> Example: 2024-06-01
                    -> Example:
                        -> LocalDate date = LocalDate.now();

                -> LocalTime:
                    -> Represents a time without date.
                    -> Example: 10:30:00
                    -> Example:
                        -> LocalTime time = LocalTime.now();

                -> LocalDateTime:
                    -> Represents a date and time without timezone.
                    -> Example: 2024-06-01T10:30:00
                    -> Example:
                        -> LocalDateTime dt = LocalDateTime.now();

                -> ZonedDateTime:
                    -> Represents a date and time with timezone.
                    -> Example: 2024-06-01T10:30:00+05:30[Asia/Kolkata]
                    -> Example:
                        -> ZonedDateTime zoned =
                                ZonedDateTime.now(
                                    ZoneId.of("Asia/Kolkata")
                                );

                -> OffsetDateTime:
                    -> Represents a date and time with an offset from UTC(Coordinated Universal Time).
                    -> Example: 2024-06-01T10:30:00+05:30
                    -> Difference:
                        -> Contains only UTC offset.
                        -> Does not contain complete timezone rules like DST(Daylight Saving Time).

                -> Instant:
                    -> Represents a machine timestamp or a point in time in UTC.
                    -> Example: 2024-06-01T10:30:00Z
                    -> Mostly used in:
                        -> Logging
                        -> Distributed systems
                        -> Databases
                        -> Server-side applications

                -> Duration:
                    -> Represents a time-based amount.
                    -> Works with hours, minutes, seconds, nanoseconds.
                    -> Example: PT2H30M
                    -> Meaning:
                        -> P = Period designator
                        -> T = Time section starts
                        -> 2H = 2 Hours
                        -> 30M = 30 Minutes
                    -> Example:
                        -> Duration duration =
                                Duration.ofHours(2);

                -> Period:
                    -> Represents a date-based amount.
                    -> Works with years, months, and days.
                    -> Example: P1Y2M3D
                    -> Meaning:
                        -> P = Period designator
                        -> 1Y = 1 Year
                        -> 2M = 2 Months
                        -> 3D = 3 Days
                    -> Example:
                        -> Period period =
                                Period.ofDays(10);

                -> Clock:
                    -> Represents a time source.
                    -> Used for:
                        -> Current time retrieval
                        -> Testing
                        -> Mocking time in applications
                    -> Example:
                        -> Clock clock = Clock.systemUTC();

                -> ZoneId:
                    -> Represents a timezone ID.
                    -> Example:
                        -> ZoneId.of("Asia/Kolkata")

                -> ZoneOffset:
                    -> Represents offset from UTC.
                    -> Example:
                        -> +05:30

        -> java.time.format:
            -> Contains classes for formatting and parsing date and time objects, such as DateTimeFormatter.

            -> Important class in java.time.format package:

                -> DateTimeFormatter:
                    -> Used for formatting and parsing date and time objects.
                    -> Thread-safe and immutable.
                    -> Provides predefined formatters like:
                        -> ISO_LOCAL_DATE
                        -> ISO_LOCAL_TIME
                        -> ISO_LOCAL_DATE_TIME

                    -> Custom Pattern Example:
                        -> DateTimeFormatter formatter =
                                DateTimeFormatter.ofPattern(
                                    "dd/MM/yyyy"
                                );

                    -> Common Pattern Symbols:

                        -> dd   -> Day
                        -> MM   -> Month number
                        -> MMM  -> Month short name
                        -> yyyy -> Year
                        -> HH   -> Hour(24-hour format)
                        -> mm   -> Minutes
                        -> ss   -> Seconds

                    -> Example:
                        -> LocalDate date =
                                LocalDate.now();

                        -> String output =
                                date.format(formatter);

                -> DateTimeFormatterBuilder:
                    -> Used for building complex date and time formatters with custom patterns and optional sections.

                    -> Works using Builder Pattern.

                    -> Step-by-step understanding:
                        -> Create empty formatter builder.
                        -> Add formatting rules.
                        -> Convert builder into formatter using toFormatter().

                    -> Example:
                        -> DateTimeFormatter formatter =
                                new DateTimeFormatterBuilder()
                                        .appendPattern(
                                            "dd/MM/yyyy"
                                        )
                                        .toFormatter();

                    -> Output:
                        -> 01/06/2024

                    -> Useful when:
                        -> Optional sections needed.
                        -> Multiple parsing formats needed.
                        -> Complex formatting rules required.

                    -> Example with optional section:
                        -> DateTimeFormatter formatter =
                                new DateTimeFormatterBuilder()
                                        .appendPattern(
                                            "dd/MM/yyyy"
                                        )
                                        .optionalStart()
                                        .appendPattern(
                                            " HH:mm"
                                        )
                                        .optionalEnd()
                                        .toFormatter();

                    -> Accepts:
                        -> 01/06/2024
                        -> 01/06/2024 10:30

                -> DecimalStyle:
                    -> Used for formatting numbers in date and time objects according to a specific locale.

                    -> Helps in:
                        -> Digit formatting
                        -> Decimal separators
                        -> Locale-specific number formatting

                    -> Example:
                        -> DecimalStyle decimalStyle =
                                DecimalStyle.of(Locale.US);

                    -> Output Example:
                        -> 1,000,000

        -> java.time.temporal:
            -> Contains classes for working with temporal fields and units.

            -> Mainly used by:
                -> Framework developers
                -> Library writers
                -> Advanced date manipulation

            -> Important interfaces/classes:

                -> Temporal:
                    -> Base interface for date-time objects.

                -> TemporalField:
                    -> Represents a field such as:
                        -> YEAR
                        -> MONTH_OF_YEAR
                        -> DAY_OF_MONTH

                -> TemporalUnit:
                    -> Represents units such as:
                        -> DAYS
                        -> MONTHS
                        -> YEARS
                        -> HOURS

                -> ChronoUnit:
                    -> Common implementation of TemporalUnit.

                    -> Example:
                        -> long days =
                                ChronoUnit.DAYS.between(
                                    startDate,
                                    endDate
                                );

                -> TemporalAdjuster:
                    -> Used to adjust dates.

                    -> Example:
                        -> Get next Sunday.

                    -> Example:
                        -> LocalDate nextSunday =
                                LocalDate.now()
                                        .with(
                                            TemporalAdjusters.next(
                                                DayOfWeek.SUNDAY
                                            )
                                        );

                -> TemporalAdjusters:
                    -> Utility class containing predefined adjusters.

                    -> Common methods:
                        -> firstDayOfMonth()
                        -> lastDayOfMonth()
                        -> next()
                        -> previous()

        -> java.time.chrono:
            -> Contains classes for working with different calendar systems.

            -> By default Java uses ISO-8601 Gregorian calendar.

            -> Supports other calendar systems such as:

                -> JapaneseChronology
                -> ThaiBuddhistChronology
                -> HijrahChronology
                -> MinguoChronology

            -> Example:
                -> HijrahDate hijrahDate =
                        HijrahDate.now();

            -> Useful for:
                -> International applications
                -> Region-specific calendars
                -> Religious calendar systems

        -> java.time.zone:
            -> Contains classes related to timezone rules and timezone handling.

            -> Important classes:

                -> ZoneRules:
                    -> Contains timezone rules like DST changes.

                -> ZoneOffsetTransition:
                    -> Represents transition between offsets.

            -> Useful for:
                -> Global applications
                -> Airline systems
                -> International scheduling
                -> Cloud applications

    -> Difference between Duration and Period:

        -> Duration:
            -> Time-based.
            -> Works with seconds and nanoseconds.
            -> Used with LocalTime or Instant.

        -> Period:
            -> Date-based.
            -> Works with years, months, days.
            -> Used with LocalDate.

    -> Difference between ZonedDateTime and OffsetDateTime:

        -> ZonedDateTime:
            -> Contains complete timezone information.
            -> Handles DST changes.
            -> Example:
                -> Asia/Kolkata

        -> OffsetDateTime:
            -> Contains only UTC offset.
            -> Does not contain timezone rules.
            -> Example:
                -> +05:30

    -> Commonly used predefined formatters:

        -> DateTimeFormatter.ISO_LOCAL_DATE
        -> DateTimeFormatter.ISO_LOCAL_TIME
        -> DateTimeFormatter.ISO_LOCAL_DATE_TIME
        -> DateTimeFormatter.ISO_ZONED_DATE_TIME

    -> Real-world use cases:

        -> Banking systems
        -> REST APIs
        -> Microservices
        -> Logging systems
        -> Scheduling applications
        -> Distributed systems
        -> Cloud-native applications

    -> Important Interview Questions:

        -> Why is new Date-Time API better?
            -> Immutable
            -> Thread-safe
            -> Better design
            -> Better timezone handling

        -> Why is SimpleDateFormat unsafe?
            -> Mutable and not thread-safe.

        -> Which class represents machine timestamp?
            -> Instant

        -> Which class should be used for timezone-aware date and time?
            -> ZonedDateTime

        -> Difference between LocalDateTime and ZonedDateTime?
            -> LocalDateTime has no timezone.
            -> ZonedDateTime contains timezone information.

        -> Which package handles formatting/parsing?
            -> java.time.format

        -> Which package handles non-ISO calendars?
            -> java.time.chrono

        -> Which package handles timezone rules?
            -> java.time.zone